 and their descendants. Semchuk describes how lives and society have been shaped by acts of legislated discrimination and how to move toward greater reconciliation, remembrance, and healing. This is necessary reading for anyone seeking to understand the cross-cultural and intergenerational consequences of Canada’s first national internment operations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xConcentration campszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xPrisoners and prisons, Canadian. 4aArt & Performance / Art & Design. 4aArt & Performance. 4aHistory / Canadian History. 4aHistory / Oral History. 4aHistory / Ukrainian History. 4aHistory. 7aPhotography / Photoessays & Documentaries.2bisacsh  aOral History / Cultural Memory / Ukrainian Studies.1 aBudney, Jen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177212439240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781772124392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781772124392/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles